100%

Different languages don't even treat this equivalently. In Ruby the sum of ASCII ords for "僕は日本語分を話します。" is 6331.

In Python, it is 239404.
In Perl, it is 6331.
In JS, it is 239404.
In C++, it is -2885.
In C#, it is 239404.
In Go, it is 239404.
In Bash, it is 239404.

This should never have been allowed to be approved, and definitely not for Reverse mode!

C++ code (not sure why it gives a -ve):
#include <iostream>
#include <numeric>
int main() {
    std::string a; std::cin >> a;
    std::cout << std::accumulate(a.begin(), a.end(), 0);
}

The following codes will output the correct values of 239404 (all tried in CG IDE).

Ruby:
unicode_value = "僕は日本語分を話します。".chars.map(&:ord).sum
puts unicode_value

Perl:
use utf8;
my $sum = 0;
$sum += ord($_) for split('', "僕は日本語分を話します。");
print "$sum\n";

C++:
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
int main() {
    std::u32string s = U"僕は日本語分を話します。";
    int sum = 0;
    for (char32_t c : s) {
        sum += static_cast<int>(c);
    }
    std::cout << sum << std::endl;
}


